After 105 years on earth our beloved Aunt Dokey went home to be with the Lord yesterday.

For those who read my book or know my story, you know how this amazing woman changed the trajectory of my life. I wouldn’t be where I am and who I am without Aunt Dokey. 

I was blessed with the opportunity to see her last month while I was in NYC for the Plane premiere. And I sensed that it would be my last time seeing her. She was still sharp and had her bearings, but she was tired and sad. She was ready to leave this world. It may sound crazy, but I’m happy for her and I know she’ll be watching as her family continues to run our races.

Thank you for everything, Aunt Dokey. Love you always and we’ll see you on the other side🙏🏿

#Legend #Superwoman

Our Matriarch/Queen has fallen, but her legacy and crown shall endure forever.

She kept getting after it (working out) until she slipped and fell last year. 

She held my Mama @paulineadeleke in her arms and prayed over her when she was a baby.

She held me and my brother @madeleke75 in her arms and prayed for us when we were babies.

And she held my kids and nephews in her arms and prayed over them when they were babies.

For those who read my book and know my story, then you know I wouldn’t be where I am today and who I am without Aunt Dokey.

And she loved #Jesus with all her heart.

Rest Easy Aunt Dokey and we’ll see you on the other side. In the meantime we’re going to honor you by continuing to crush life and bless others.

🙏🏿9/30/1918-2/23/23🙏🏿

Yesterday we lost another SEAL Legend and brother to suicide. Senior Chief @MikeDay5326 🙏🏿🔱. 

A couple of years ago my family and I were leaving church when my phone rang. It was Mike, which meant I had to take it. What I promised my wife would be a quick call turned into 2 hour conversation about life, storytelling and writing.

Mike was struggling for a number of reasons I won’t get into, but what we discussed on that call seemed to give him hope. He was in the process of writing his life story, which became therapeutic for him and he wanted to ensure that it was written in a way that inspired people without exploiting the community. 

On that call, Mike talked me through his story, which was indeed beat out in a way that helped others and didn’t edify himself. I explained this to Mike, and I remember a sense of calm and hope coming over him.

That calm and hope derived from the fact that through his story he would indeed be able to keep doing what he joined the Navy to do— help and serve people.

The man was all about others and never about himself. He was a true TEAMMATE. And even the thought that he would come off selfish or self-edifying threw him into a mental tail spin. 

I know he is finally at peace. And I know his story and legacy will continue to serve and bless others.

We went from rich to poor overnight.

I’m standing with a friend 18 flights up on the roof of her building. We watch as smoke rises into the the sky. She tells me, “My cousin is a waitress at Windows Of The World at the top of the North Tower and she has two kids. I hope she can make it out.”

My heart sank for two reasons:

1. My friend’s cousin, a single-mom from the Bronx, was now standing in the face of death.

2. My father once served on the Board of the World Trade Center and commissioned his friend, the architect of the WTC, Minoru Yamasak to design twin towers for what is now Banana Island.

Those are two of many reasons why I will #neverforget #911

Epilogue: Her cousin was never found🙏🏿
